  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes, good approach — but keep glossing light during the 道德仁义礼 experiment to preserve pacing",
    "content": "**Yes, this is the right approach. One concern and one suggestion.**\n\n**Concern: the 道德仁义礼 passage is not a quotation --- it is an experiment.** The Laozi line (\"故失道而后德，失德而后仁...\") is a genuine classical quotation and should get the full treatment: original wenyan preserved, glossed English translation, then English thereafter.\n\nBut the author's own analysis that follows --- the step-by-step reversal through 现象礼 -> 现象义 -> 现象仁 -> 德 -> 道 --- is modern Chinese, not wenyan. More importantly, it is a philosophical experiment being performed on the reader. The glossing format must not slow down the experiential progression. If every occurrence of 现象礼 is accompanied by \"(phenomenal ritual, xianxiang li)\" the reader will be processing metadata instead of undergoing the reversal. Gloss the 现象- terms once at first occurrence, then use clean English for the rest of the passage so the reader can move through the sequence at the pace the experiment requires.\n\n**Suggestion: distinguish between the author's technical compounds and the classical terms.** The classical terms (仁, 义, 礼, 德, 道) have long translation histories and the reader may want the Chinese and romanization as anchors. The author's coinages (现象礼, 现象仁, 现象义) do not have prior translation histories --- they are the author's own compounds, and the English renderings (\"phenomenal ritual,\" \"phenomenal humaneness,\" \"phenomenal rightness\") are self-explanatory once glossed once. So:\n\n- Classical terms: Chinese + romanization on first occurrence, then English only. Reasonable.\n- Author's compounds: English gloss once, then English only. No need for romanization --- these are not terms the reader will look up elsewhere.\n\nThis keeps the apparatus proportional to the reader's actual needs."
  }
}
